Subject to certain constraints, the smaller array is “broadcast” across the larger array so that they have compatible shapes. It does this without making needless copies of data and usually leads to efficient algorithm implementations. There are, however, cases where broadcasting is a bad idea because it leads to inefficient use of memory that slows computation.

This forces the model to learn a continuous latent space that generalizes well. ## Answer

cloneElement is used to pass props into children. For example, you have a component that have children like this:
```
<Parent>
  <Child name="Bob" />
  <Child name="Jane" />
  <Child name="Mary" />
</Parent>
```
And you want to pass props to each child, you can do it like this:
```
const Parent = ({ children }) => {
  return React.Children.map(children, child => {
    return React.cloneElement(child, {
      count: 10
    })
  })
}
```
Then each child will receive a prop called count with value of 10 .
